(127, 'Coalyard Miniature Railway', 'The line was first opened in 1988 at the Severn Valley RailwayÂ’s Kidderminster Station. It was originally constructed as a 100 metre long 8 Â¾Â” gauge railway (5Â” and 3 Â½Â” gauge laid next to one another) to allow us to operate a 5Â” King Class Locomotive and a 3 Â½Â” Hall class locomotive which were placed on loan to the railway. The track was also unusual as it was completely welded and had no fishplates. The sleepers were also pressed onto the rail, which is unusual.A new 7 Â¼Â” gauge track laid using heavy duty Aluminium rail was laid adjacent in 1990. This line was gradually extended until it reached the far end of the car park. After a short while the original line was removed to make way for a new walkway from the SVRÂ’s car park to the station alongside the current track.. The line originally used wooden sleepers although as these wore out they were replaced with plastic sleepers. The railway got its name from a coal merchant who used to operate alongside our terminus station until he left the site in 2004.The line is approximately 400 yards long, with a further extension of 100 yards underway. The line is parallel and close to the main SVR running tracks which at times allows parallel running between the miniature railway locomotives and SVR locomotives.Operation is usually with petrol or battery powered locomotives, however steam locomotives do run on occasions. Coaching stock is a mixture of sit astride and sit in coaches. There is also a rake of narrow gauge wagons.<br />\r\n', 3, '', 'Station Approach', '', 'Kidderminster, Worcestershire', 15, 52.3847, -2.23924, 1, '', '0', 'www.freewebs.com/coalyardminiaturerailway', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(129, 'Train Mountain', 'Train Mountain Railroad Museum is a non-profit organization dedicated to the preservation of our railroad heritage. It is located in Southern Oregon on over 2000 acres of Ponderosa Pine forest in Klamath County, the home of Crater Lake National Park.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTrain Mountain currently has 69,900 feet (13Â¼ miles) of 7Â½&#8243; gauge mainline track and 133,250 feet (25Â¼ miles) of total trackage, which includes yards, sidings, and connector tracks. In the 2004 Guinness World RecordsÂ™ Train Mountain is recognized as the "Longest Miniature Hobby Railroad".<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe also have a great selection of train merchandise and souvenirs. We feature train puzzles, train collectibles, train pedal cars, 7Â½&#8243; train and track supplies and one of the largest train pin stores online! Visit our store to see our complete inventory. ', 3, '', '36941 South Chiloquin Road', '97624-9728', 'Chiloquin, Oregon', 16, 42.5585, -121.887, 1, '', '0', 'www.trainmountain.org', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(130, 'Ironhorse Park Miniature Railway', 'Iron Horse Park is a re-creation in miniature of the railway pioneer days in the Canadian West. When complete there will be a 1 1/2 mile miniature train interpretive journey for kids of all ages. The journey will represent the Canadian Pacific Railway from the prairies to the coast. The trip will climb mountains, cross trestles, through tunnels on both steam and diesel locomotives. Along the route you will travel past small scale farmsteads, towns and industries typical of the area.', 3, '', '820 Railway Gate', 'AB T4B', 'Airdrie', 4, 51.286, -114.022, 1, '', '67', 'www.ironhorsepark.net', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(131, 'Big Boots & Western R. R.', 'The railroad currently features 1 1/2 miles of mainline, with 65 ft. radii throughout, with a maximum grade of 2% and two separate yards. This track is setup to approximate the SAL and the ACL as they head south from Ocala, FL towards Tampa, Leesburg and Sanford. A drive through transfer table makes for easy unloading allowing access to the steaming bays or you can transfer directly to the main yard. The main yard is lighted and has 11 double ended tracks for storage of up to 200 cars. Our car barn/engine house holds 50 pieces of rolling stock. Future plans call for 4+ miles of mainline and more yards. The railroad features many long straight tracks, sidings, refreshing, winding tracks through the wooded areas. Bi-directional running provides plenty of meets and passes and variations on running options. We have made a some improvements this year. Working block signals now control all movements over the mainline. The industrial park is starting to take shape and is used during Card Order meets, which have been well received. The mainline has been extended and now the transit time is almost 1/2 hour. We now have more than 70 switches providing a lot of operation, with more being added as time allows. The Fort Doing siding has been extended with plans on adding several more tracks at that location. A G gauge layout is located near the Steaming Bays. There is plenty of parking for campers and shady areas if you have a tent. Electricity is limited to lights and fans. We also have a bathroom and shower. On cool evenings there is usually a campfire. Due to the grades, you must be able to control and stop your train on them. Lights on the engine and last car are needed for night running. Bring your FRS radios. Check the schedule for the Card Order sessions and other meets.', 4, '', '', 'FL', 'Candler', 16, 29.0713, -81.9727, 0, '', '68', 'www.bigbootsrr.com', 150, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(132, 'West Tocoi & Bostwick RR', 'This track boasts two separate railroads comprising a 7 1/2 gauge (3600 ft) and 2 ft gauge with four different areas where they cross.  2 ft gauge has over 6200 ft of mainline (6600 ft planned). Outer loop is complete. 350 ft remains to close inner loop. Two mainline wyes for turning the train. Self contained camping is available.**   Road crossings, drive-thru unloading facilities, steaming bays have all been upgraded this year prior to the FLS Winter Meet.  Six yard tracks (250 ft) near the station now allow the engineers to take a break without blocking the mainline as well as much in the way of track extensions. Also, an ever-growing automated signaling system.', 3, '', '', '', 'Jacksonville', 16, 29.8445, -81.5821, 0, '', '69', 'www.neflsri.com', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(133, 'Tradewinds & Atlantic Railroad', 'The trains that operate in Tradewinds Park are one-eighth life-size, or scaled at 1-1/2" per foot. This makes them eleven times bigger than the typical HO scale train you might have in your home. The track gauge is 7-1/2", a world-wide standard that allows us to host visitors from all over North and South America, England, Europe, Australia, and Africa. Steam, batteries, or small gas engines power the locomotives. Steam locomotives might burn coal, propane gas, or fuel oil depending on the whims of the builder. Models of Diesel-Electric locomotives using batteries give quiet dependable operation, while gasoline-powered locomotives give the ability to operate all day.', 3, '', '3600 West, Sample Road', 'FL33073', 'Coconut Creek', 16, 26.2743, -80.1764, 1, '', '70', 'www.livesteamers.org', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(134, 'Manatee Central Rail Road', '7 1/2 gauge, 4 3/4 gauge, Gage 1, a pond for steam boats, a shady area for hit and miss, and bring and brag.**   This track covers two five-acre private sites that comprise a well laid out track plan with four separate unloading areas, two separate steaming bays and two hydraulic lifts. One mile of mainline and one mile of sidings and yards.  Self contained camping is available on limited basis at the meets.  Call to check availability of open sites. NEW, minimum radius on track is now 52 ft.', 4, '', '', '', 'Parrish', 16, 33.7377, -87.2828, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(135, 'Ridge Live Steamers', '7 1/2 gauge, 4200+ feet of main line and 6000+ feet of sidings and yards built in an old orange grove. It boasts many bridges, grades up to 1 1/2 % and a by-pass track with 3.3% to challenge the ability of engineers and equipment, bi-directional signaled track and a tunnel.  There are restrooms, shower facilities, picnic pavilion, passenger loading station and a drive through hydraulic unloading facility.  About 36 campsites with water and electric hookups.  Camping by prior approval.', 3, '', 'N Scenic Hwy', 'FL33838', 'Dundee', 16, 28.0076, -81.5951, 1, '', '71', 'www.geocities.com/~ridgeclub', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(136, 'Largo Central Railroad', 'This track is located in a City Park that has a good unloading area and yard storage tracks.  A well thought out track plan makes for an interesting and enjoyable ride.  Public rides are given on the 1st full weekend of each month.  To run on this track all engines must be equipped with a headlight and a rear light on the end of the train even during the day.  It becomes apparent for this as you go through the recently installed tunnel that is pitch black in the middle.  Another interesting feature is the ride over the pond. Much new track and new crossties are now being installed.', 3, '', 'Central Park Drive', 'FL33771', 'Largo', 16, 27.9143, -82.7861, 1, '', '72', 'www.lcrailroad.com', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(137, 'Locodefi (Institute Technique Saint-Joseph)', 'These realizations, wich have begun in the course of the schoolyear 1997-1998 were inaugurated on the 12th May 2000.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring this weekend, more than 2000 visitors came to discover the network and to visit the great exhibition about the railway, which had been set up by the school secretarial section.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe network,developed on an area of 2 hectares, includes 600 metres railway, a roundhouse for the maintenance, two watertowers and a markings cabin.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe railway and the switches were realized by the sections "Machines-tools" and "Soldering". The buildings were constructed by the sections "Buildings" and "Woodwork". The section "Electricity" was responsible for the electrical feeding and the markings railway.', 3, '', 'La Louviere', '7070', 'Le Roeulx', 3, 50.5028, 4.10889, 0, '', '73', 'users.win.be/W0080404/menuengl.htm', 151, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(139, 'Los Angeles Live Steamers', 'The Los Angeles Live Steamers Railroad Museum (LALSRM) is a non-profit 501(c)(3) public benefit corporation that was founded in 1956. It was started by train enthusiasts for the purpose of educating people in railroad history and lore and also to further the avocation of live steam, gas-mechanical and electronic railroad technology.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe operate our 7Â½" gauge model trains for the general public to ride free of charge from 11 am - 3 pm every Sunday (weather permitting). except for the Sunday before Memorial Day and the first Sunday in October. The gate is open from 10:45 am to 3 pm. Train rides begin at 11 am. We also have extensive layouts for 4Â¾" and 3Â½" gauge model trains.', 3, '', '5202 Zoo Drive', 'CA90027', 'Los Angeles', 16, 34.1548, -118.302, 1, '', '75', 'www.lals.org', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(142, 'Alderney Miniature Railway', ' The Alderney miniature railway is on Alderney, one of the Channel Islands. It is an added attraction to the standard gauge Â‘Alderney RailwayÂ’. The railway is situated within Mannez Quarry and is a circular route of 400 yards. The line is operated by one petrol locomotive and passengers are pulled by three sit-astride carriages or a 1st class sit-in carriage.', 3, '', '', '', 'Alderney', 15, 49.7189, -2.19536, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(143, 'Audley End Miniature Railway', 'The Audley End Miniature Railway is a grand miniature railway owned by Lord Braybrooke, trains depart from Audley End station which is opposite the houses gates. Your journey begins by passing by the shed area where you will see some lovely locomotives all but one built by David Curwen. You then come into a woodland area where you will cross over the River Fulfen and River Cam. Whilst in the woodlands you pass Forest deep halt and go through a long tunnel. You then come back on your original route, round another loop and back into the station. This railway has a wide range of locomotives and teddy bears too!', 3, '', 'Audley End', '', 'Saffron Walden', 15, 52.0193, 0.217811, 1, '', '76', 'www.audley-end-railway.co.uk', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(144, 'Bankside Miniature Railway', 'The Bankside Miniature Railway first opened in 1977 when the owner installed this railway after running at Beaulieu Gardens for a few years in the sixties. The railway is unusual as being on elevated track and is the only 8 Â¼ inch gauge railway in the country. Trains are pulled by Â‘CarolynÂ’ which was built in 1924. Trains run from Brambridge Station and run round a balloon loop, returning to the station. Then the whole train is revolved on a 35ft Turntable ready for its next journey. The line was extended from End to End to its present situation in 1999. The line is now dual gauge so more engines can operate on the railway.', 3, '', 'Kiln Lane', 'SO50 6HT', 'Brambridge', 15, 50.9979, -1.33491, 1, '', '0', 'banksiderailway.wetpaint.com/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(145, 'Barleylands Miniature Steam Railway', 'The Barleylands Miniature Steam Railway opened in 1989 utilising the track and most of the rolling stock from the North Benfleet Miniature Railway. Since then one new locomotive, Gowrie has been added. Normally operated as two sections trains run from Museum to Littlewood Junction and return and Boot Fair to Littlewood Junction and return, the latter usually only on Sunday mornings. From the Shed area behind the museum, this line drops down in a C shape to a run round loop at Littlewood Junction. From there a further line runs, more or less straight to Boot Fair Station. Because of its layout the railway is operated in two halves. On your journey you will pass go over two level crossings and your journey will take around 10 minutes. There are six steam locomotives, two of which are not operational at present.', 3, '', 'Barleylands Road', 'CM11 2UD', 'Billericay', 15, 51.6019, 0.445703, 1, '', '77', 'www.barleylands.co.uk/miniature_steam_railway.htm', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(147, 'Beer Heights Light Railway', 'The Beer Heights Light Railway was opened in 1975 by Reverend W Awdry, creator of Â‘Thomas The Tank EngineÂ’ built to complement the permanent model railway exhibition. It ran from Much Natter Station to the engine sheds. Over the year the line was extended and now gives a mile run from Much Natter Station round a complicated loop and back. On your journey, there are views of the countryside and gardens of Pecorama and also exciting railway features like a tunnel, two signal boxes, two level crossings and a bridge. The journey takes around approx 14 minutes. The railway used to be operated by a battery electric and a saddle tank when the line first opened, but these were disposed of soon after. The line is now run by seven steam locomotives, one diesel locomotive and a battery operated tram which runs at peak times a shuttle service down the mine branch.', 3, '', 'Mare Lane', 'EX12 3NA', 'Seaton, Beer', 15, 50.6978, -3.10135, 1, '', '0', 'www.peco-uk.com/?p=BHLR#info', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(149, 'Belton Light Railway', 'The Belton House Miniature Railway runs in the grounds of the beautiful Belton House. The station is situated next to the childrenÂ’s adventure playground and from here, trains run over a level crossing and through a tunnel to reach the end of the line. Trains then reverse back to the station on the 500yd track. There is a footbridge and a two road engine shed at the station. The trains are run by the diesel locomotive. Originally trains were steam worked and has been operated by other Mardyke locos.', 3, '', 'Belton House', 'NG32 2LS', 'Grantham', 15, 52.944, -0.619837, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(150, 'Bickington Steam Railway', 'This railway opened using equipment from the Suffolk Wildlife Park, some of which had been originally used at Rudyard Lake. Since opening, the railway has been extended twice, the most recent extension opening in 2006 to the new Riverside station. The railway now provides transport for visitors between the main car park and the leisure park.Riverside station is adjacent to the main car park for Trago Mills and has 3 tracks which end in a turntable. From here, trains cross a road by an automatic level crossing and run alongside a river, before crossing the river. The railway then joins the original circuit, which loops around and across itself several times Â– at one point there are 6 parallel tracks, all on different levels. The second station Â“Trago CentralÂ” has two platforms and is situated in the Leisure Park area. After leaving Â“Trago CentralÂ” trains pass over an impressive 23 pier viaduct and pass the workshop & engine shed before heading back to Riverside station, where the locomotive is turned and run round the train.', 3, 'Trago Mills Shopping & Leisure Centre', 'Staplehill Road', 'TQ12 6JB', 'Stover', 15, 50.5551, -3.66577, 1, '', '0', 'www.trago.co.uk/newton_abbot.htm', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(152, 'Brechin Castle Centre', 'The Brechin Castle Centre Railway consists of a 300yd simple circuit next to a lake. Trains are hauled by the petrol locomotive', 3, '', '', 'DD9 6RL', 'Angus', 15, 56.8482, -2.84752, 0, '', '79', 'www.brechincastlecentre.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(153, 'Bressingham Garden Railway', 'The Bressingham Garden Railway first opened in 1964 and was 9 Â½ inch gauge. Trains were pulled by Â‘PrincessÂ’ until 1994 and another steam engine built by A.E Salt until the 1970s. After working for many years as the sole motive power Â‘PrincessÂ’ retired and the line was relaid as a 10 Â¼ inch gauge line in 1995. This is the present line today. Trains run from the Garden Station and go through the late Alan BloomÂ’s garden passing the bed and breakfast house travelling round a balloon loop and then returning to the station via the same route. The trains are pulled by saddle tank Â‘Alan BloomÂ’ which was built in the workshops at Bressingham.', 3, 'Bressingham Steam Museum', 'Thetford Road', 'IP22 2AB', 'Bressingham', 15, 52.3848, 1.05713, 1, '', '0', 'www.bressingham.co.uk/journeys/gardenrw.htm', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(154, 'Brockwell Park Miniature Railway', ' The Railway is situated in the grounds of Brockwell Park adjacent to the Lido, the line runs parallel to Dulwich Road for about 220 meters. Built by Roland Baker, the line first opened on 1st June 2002 by the late lord mayor of Lambeth and sold to the current owners in Feb. 2006.', 3, '', 'Herne Hill, Dulwich Road', 'SE24', 'London', 15, 51.4526, -0.103305, 1, '', '80', 'www.brockwellpark.com/MiniatureRailway/MiniRailway.html', 153, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(157, 'Buckfastleigh Miniature Railway', 'The Buckfastleigh Miniature Railway is situated at Buckfastleigh Station on the South Devon Railway. It originally opened in 1977 as the Riverside Miniature Railway and trains were pulled by Â‘YeoÂ’ which was a 2-6-2 tank steam engine. This closed in 1983 and Yeo moved to the Gorse Blossom Railway. The line reopened in 1993 and is a circular line that runs around the picnic area behind the standard gauge locomotive sheds. Trains are pulled by either steam or petrol locomotives.', 3, '', '', 'TQ11 0DZ', 'Buckfastleigh', 15, 50.4823, -3.76782, 1, '', '82', 'www.southdevonrailway.org/News-and-Press-Releases/Minature-Railway.html', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(158, 'Bure Valley Railway', 'The Bure Valley Railway opened in 1990 and runs over a nine mile section of former Great Eastern track bed between the ancient market town of Aylsham and the "Capital of the Norfolk Broads ", Wroxham.<br />\r\nWe start our journey at Aylsham, headquarters of the line which includes the locomotive workshops, large restaurant and souvenir shop, all with full wheelchair access. After passing through the idyllic Norfolk villages of Buxton, Brampton , and Coltishall we arrive at Wroxham. Originally operated by locoÂ’s hired from other railways such as the Romney Hythe & Dymchurch and Bressingham. The Bure Valley Railway now boasts five steam locos and three diesels, purpose built or adapted for the many gradients of the line.', 3, '', 'Norwich Road', 'NR11 6BW', 'Aylsham', 15, 52.7912, 1.25565, 1, '', '0', 'www.bvrw.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(159, 'Carnfunnock Family Fun Zone Miniature Railway', 'The Carnfunnock Family Fun Zone Miniature Railway is a 650yd dumb bell loop railway with trains running from Carnfunnock Halt, which is one of the loops. Trains are operated by one petrol locomotive.', 3, '', 'Coast Road', 'BT40 2QG', 'Larne', 15, 54.8773, -5.83168, 0, '', '0', 'www.carnfunnock.com/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(161, 'Cleethorpes Coast Light Railway', 'This very popular seaside railway opened in 1971 as a 14 Â½ inch gauge railway but has recently been regauged to 15inch gauge. Trains run from Lakeside station which is near the theme park Pleasure Island up a hill, then past the shed area. It then runs alongside the sea wall and over a 40yd viaduct to Kingsway station which is next to the Leisure Centre. Recently the line has been extended nearer to Pleasure Island, and now a spur from Lakeside runs down the coast to North Sea Lane Station. The railway used to be operated by a pair of Severn lamb locomotives but now steam trains are regular. Sian and Katie used to be here, but they have moved to Windmill Animal Farm. It is also worth mentioning that recently they acquired the Sutton Miniature Railway rolling stock which are now housed in a specially built museum/shed and also run on the railway frequently.', 3, '', 'Kings Road', 'DN35 0AG', 'Cleethorpes', 15, 53.5435, -0.00994295, 1, '', '84', 'www.cleethorpescoastlightrailway.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(162, 'Combe Martin Wildlife Park Railway', 'The Combe Martin Wildlife Park Railway (now nicknamed the Earthquake Train Ride) first opened in 1989 and gave a run of around 150 yards. In 1991 the line was extended to its present situation. The lines runs from a station and runs past a Gold Mining Shanty Town and an artificial Stream which when the train runs past, 6000 gallons of water rush down against a deflecting wall and splashes all the passengers. Trains are pulled by a Severn Lamb Â‘Rio GrandeÂ’ loco. The engine and stock used to be in blue livery but have been changed to green recently.', 3, '', 'Leigh Road', 'EX34 0NG', 'Combe Martin', 15, 51.1892, -4.00337, 1, '', '85', 'www.dinosaur-park.com/earthquake.htm', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(163, 'Craigtoun Miniature Railway', 'The Craigtoun Miniature Railway is situated in Craigtoun Park. A previopus line of 7 1/4 inch gauige operated here from 1960 - 1975. The present railway used to be an end to end, but in 1996 the railway was severely altered and is now a circuit round a lake. There are numerous level crossings en route. Trains are operated by the Rio Grande steam outline engine which is named Ivor.', 3, '', '', 'KY16 8NX', 'St Andrews', 15, 56.3195, -2.83946, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(164, 'Croxteth Park Miniature Railway', 'The Croxteth Miniature Railway opened in 1981 and is located in the grounds of the big Croxteth Country Park. Trains run from one station which is called Â‘Croxteth HaltÂ’. The station has a booking office and an overall roof. Trains run from here in a clockwise direction passing through a short tunnel, allowing two runs of the circuit via a passing loop alongside the station where the next train will possibly be waiting. The whole site is totally enclosed in high mesh wire so line side photography is only possible on request. Two steam engines Â‘DennisÂ’ and Â‘EstelleÂ’ used to work here but have moved.', 3, '', 'Croxteth Hall & Country Park, Croxteth Hall', 'L12 OHB', 'Croxteth', 15, 53.4424, -2.89092, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(165, 'Dibleys Nursery Railway', 'Dibleys Nursery Railway is situated in the grounds of Dibleys Garden centre which is situated in North Wales. The railway runs through the woods and gardens. Trains are pulled by either an Exmoor steam locomotive or RMI Railworks Tram.', 3, '', 'Llanelidan', 'LL15 2LG', 'Ruthin', 15, 53.0784, -3.36259, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(166, 'Dragon Miniature Railway', 'Opened in 1999 using equipment from the Brookside Miniature Railway, this railway is continually expanding in its grounds in Wyevale Garden Centre, and now boasts a 1/2 mile line, picnic area (seasonal), tunnel and comprehensive depot area. The main station (complete with overall canopy and waiting room/shop) and picnic area halt have been completed in LMS/BR (MR) style. Tours round the sheds are available, sometimes seeing maintenance to locomotives being carried out, Steam locomotives run on Sundays and Bank Holidays. The ride lasts between 5 and 8 minutes. A drive-your-own tram is now on site', 3, '', 'Dooley Lane', '', 'Marple', 15, 53.4021, -2.0958, 1, '', '86', 'www.freewebs.com/dragonrailway/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(167, 'Exmouth Express', 'The Exmouth Express opened in 1949 and runs in a circle in one corner of this fun park which is situated on the seafront of Exmouth. The line passes through the engine shed and tunnel as it goes round and trains are pulled by a diesel loco. Steam engines operated here in the 1940s and 50s.', 3, '', '', 'EX8 2AY', 'Exmouth', 15, 50.6131, -3.40926, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(171, 'Hall Leys Park Railway', 'The Hall Leys Park Railway first opened in 1948. It has the unusual gauge of 9 Â½ inch gauge and is one of only four miniature railways of this gauge in the country. The line is a simple back and forth run with one station and a two road engine shed. Its runs alongside the River Derwent. Trains are pulled by the diesel Â‘Little DavidÂ’ which has been here since 1974 replacing the lines steam engines', 3, '', '', 'Derbyshire', 'Matlock', 15, 53.1383, -1.55517, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(172, 'Happy Mount Express', 'Happy Mount Express is situated in Happy Mount Park and is a 200yd circular railway running from the station and whilst in journey through the tunnel/shed. This long established line opened in 1956 and used to have a steam outline engine and petrol engine operating but these have both been scrapped. Now the line has a recently built diesel engine.', 3, '', 'Marine Road East', 'LA4 6AB', 'Morecambe', 15, 54.0733, -2.87105, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(173, 'Hilcote Valley Railway', 'The Hilcote Valley Railway opened in 1993 and was designed by Roger Greatrex, a popular miniature railway engineer. The line is a circular route leaving a smart landscaped station which has a booking office, raised platform and a signal box. From here trains leave in a clockwise direction via a loop circuit, providing an enjoyable ride around the lake, then passing through a tunnel before returning to the platform. There is also a replica bridge.', 3, '', 'Stone Road', '', 'Eccleshall', 15, 52.8609, -2.23668, 1, '', '0', 'www.touristnetuk.com/wm/hilcote', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(174, 'Hotham Park Railway', 'The Hotham Park Railway originally opened in 1969 and was operated by Ian Allan Group who had several lines in the South of England. It has since had several reincarnations. The current line opened in 2007, after the line was removed for a year in 2006. It is a 900yd circuit that runs through woodland with the station next to a cafe. Train rides consist of two circuits. Trains are operated by an Alan Keef steam outline loco which was delivered new in 2007. ', 3, 'CTS Narrow Gauge Railways LLP', 'Hotham Park', 'PO21 1HV', 'Bognor Regis', 15, 50.7881, -0.666486, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(175, 'John F Kennedy Arboretum Miniature Railway', 'This line opened in 1990 and runs from the station which is situated 1000m from the car park of these gardens. One American style engine pulls five coaches round a 650yd track. From the station, it runs round the outer circuit and then visa the original. The driver changes the facing points by a lineside lever. This also operates a centre based signal at the junction.', 3, '', 'North Canpile', 'Wexford', 'New Ross', 7, 52.341, -6.97909, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(177, 'Knebworth Park Miniature Railway', 'This railway, which runs in the grounds of Knebworth Park, was opened in 1991 to replace a previous 2ft gauge line. The station is at the top of a short balloon loop, close to the car access to Knebworth Park and an adventure playground. From here trains run downhill before crossing to the opposite hillside. This railway is the Â“sisterÂ” line to the Vanstone Woodland Railway and locomotives sometimes move between the lines. 5 carriages at Knebworth are from Ian AllanÂ’s foray into miniature railways, as are a number of locomotives. The steam locomotive Â“PilgrimÂ” originally ran on the Wells & Walsingham Light Railway.', 3, '', 'Knebworth House', 'SG3', 'Knebworth', 15, 51.8737, -0.215333, 1, '', '0', 'www.knebworthrailway.co.nr/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(179, 'Lappa Valley Steam Railway', 'The Lappa Valley Steam Railway was founded on the trackbed of an old standard gauge railway by Eric Booth in 1974,and is now owned and operated by the Booth family.There are 3 different railways along with various other attractions.A 15Â” gauge steam railway runs from the car park at Benny Halt to East Wheal Rose, where there is a historic mine house, boating lake and other attractions. From East Wheal Rose, you can ride further along the standard gauge trackbed on the 10Â¼Â” gauge Newlyn Branch Line to Newlyn Halt, where there is childrenÂ’s play equipment. Also at East Wheal Rose is the 7Â¼Â” gauge Woodland Railway,running in a circuit around a maze.The 15Â” gauge railway uses some equipment previously at Longleat House and obtained from the failed Axe and Lyme Valley Railways project.The 10Â¼Â” gauge railway previously ran at Carlyon Bay,St Austell,and was rebuilt at Lappa Valley in time for the 1995 season. The 7Â¼Â” gauge line was initially worked by a Royal Scot but is now normally worked by a Mardyke sit-in Advanced Passenger Train.', 3, '', 'St. Newlyn East', '', 'Newquay', 15, 50.3748, -5.04157, 1, '', '0', 'www.lappavalley.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(180, 'Leasowes Miniature Railway', 'The Leasowes Miniature Railway opened in 1990 and operates along the towpath of Dudley No 2 Canal on the Birmingham Canal Navigations. The line starts in the car park and after passing through wood land arrives at the park lake. Trains are usually steam hauled being pulled by the wonderful engine Â‘Prince Edward which was built in 1936 but the petrol engine operates trains sometimes.', 3, '', 'Mucklow Hill', 'B62 8QF', 'Halesowen', 15, 52.4541, -2.03783, 1, '', '89', 'www.leasowes.bravehost.com/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(182, 'Little Didtre Light Railway', 'This line forms part of the attractions at the Hidden Valley Discovery Park nr. Launceston. The railway opened in 2003 as an end-to-end layout, and was extended in 2004 to become a circuit. On the trip the train travels through a large cutting and passes some mock old mine workings.', 3, '', '', 'PL15', 'St Thomas', 15, 50.6293, -4.44224, 1, '', '90', 'www.hiddenvalleydiscoverypark.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(183, 'Little Western Railway', 'This attractive line, the Â“sisterÂ” line to Lappa Valley, runs in a circuit close to Newquay Zoo. There is a tunnel, two stations and two bridges over a stream. The normal locomotive is a Mardyke HST, and there is a second HST which is kept as the spare loco for both here and the 7Â¼Â” line at Lappa Valley. In the past a Royal Scot and Cromar White Hymek have both run here.', 3, '', 'Trenance Gardens', '', 'Newquay', 15, 50.4132, -5.08307, 0, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(185, 'Manor Park Miniature Railway', 'The Manor Park Miniature Railway opened in 1970 is situated in Manor Park which is Â¼ mile from the town centre. Trains operate from Manor Station where there is a run round loop and carry on through Woodland to a Balloon Loop. At the moment trains are being operated end to end after recent floods. There is a carriage and engine shed on the loop. Trains are operated by a large collection of internal combustion engines, although steam engines did run here at one time.', 3, '', 'Manor Park Road', 'Derbyshire', 'Glossop', 15, 53.448, -1.93944, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(186, 'Markeaton Park Light Railway', 'This railway opened in 1989, but when taken over by John and Jane Bull in 1995, it was greatly improved and extended. Trains run from the main car park, through the park and over two major bridges to a second terminus adjacent to the play area at Mundy Halt. Most services are pulled by Â‘Markeaton LadyÂ’ which is a fantastic steam locomotive built by the Exmoor Steam Railway. There is also a deltic diesel which usually operates the first train of the day, whilst the petrol engine is currently in store. Rolling stock consists of three luxurious coaches also built by Tony Stirland at Exmoor.', 3, '', '', 'DE22', 'Derby', 15, 52.9312, -1.50435, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(187, 'Ness Islands Railway', 'The Ness Islands Railway is situated in Bught Park which is on Whin Island in Inverness. It is BritainÂ’s second most northern public miniature railway and opened in 1983. The track was relaid in 1989 along the bank of a river incorporating a 140ft span iron bridge built in 1837. The line is a dumb bell folded over on top of itself, with the station on the C shaped single line in the middle. There are presently three locomotives including a new Western delivered to the line in 2006. The steam locomotive normally operates at weekends only.', 3, '', 'Bught Park, Whin Island', 'IV3', 'Inverness', 15, 57.4605, -4.23736, 1, '', '0', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(188, 'Newby Hall Miniature Railway', 'The Newby Hall Miniature Railway first opened in 1971 and runs in the grounds of Newby Hall Estate near Ripon. The line runs parallel to the River Ure in the shape of a dumb-bell loop.<br />\r\nThe station Â‘Newby HallÂ’ is situated in the middle of the line and has a turntable and engine shed. Trains depart from here, to the first loop which has a tunnel. The train then goes back through the station onto the second loop, in which it crosses a bridge to run and return to the station. Motive Power on the railway includes a Battison built Â‘Royal ScotÂ’ however this is currently being overhauled, so trains are run by either of the two Severn Lamb locomotives.', 3, '', 'Newby Hall', 'HG4', 'Ripon', 15, 54.1003, -1.46655, 1, '', '0', 'www.newbyhall.co.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(189, 'North Bay Railway', '', 3, '', 'Burniston Road', '', 'Scarborough', 15, 54.293, -0.411327, 1, '', '0', 'www.nbr.org.uk/', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(190, 'Liliput Bahn im Prater', 'Ein groÃŸes SÃ¤ngerfest, anlÃ¤sslich zum 100. Todestag von Franz Schubert im Wiener Prater, war der ausschlagende Grund in Wien eine VergnÃ¼gungsbahn zu errichten. Die Firma Brangsch, die ja schon Erfahrung hatte, bekam den Auftrag. Am 1. Mai 1928 durften die ersten FahrgÃ¤ste die ca. 2 Kilometer lange Strecke bis zur damals noch existierenden Rotunde (1937 abgebrannt) benÃ¼tzen.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDas Publikumsinteresse entsprach anfangs aber nicht den Erwartungen. Durch die Wirtschaftskrise in den darauf folgenden Jahren wurde die eigentlich fÃ¼r den Prater vorgesehene dritte Lok fÃ¼r andere Ausstellungen verwendet. Durch die VerlÃ¤ngerung bis zum Stadion 1933 erhoffte man sich, die Frequenz zu erhÃ¶hen.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nErst 1938 wurde das Interesse an der Liliputbahn grÃ¶ÃŸer. Eine dritte Lokomotive wurde danach auch bestellt, und 1942 in den Dienst gestellt. ', 3, '', 'Antifaschismusplatz', '1020', 'Wien', 1, 48.2157, 16.3966, 1, '', '91', 'www.liliputbahn.com', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(191, 'Donauparkbahn', 'Die Schwester der "Liliputbahn im Prater"<br />\r\nwurde als Ausstellungsbahn zur Internationalen Gartenausstellung 1964 erÃ¶ffnet, und entzÃ¼ckt durch die SchÃ¶nheit ihrer Strecke. Sie erreichen die Donauparkbahn mit dem Auto (Parkplatz Donauturm ebenso bei der ArbeiterstrandbadstraÃŸe), oder nach einem 5minÃ¼tigen Spaziergang von der U-Bahn-Station "Alte Donau" (U1) zur Haltestelle Rosenschau der Donauparkbahn.', 3, '', 'DonauturmstraÃŸe', '1210', 'Wien', 1, 48.2405, 16.4095, 1, '', '92', 'www.liliputbahn.com', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
